TY  - JOUR
T1  - Self-Fulfilling Prophecy as a Management Tool: Harnessing Pygmalion
AU  - Eden, Dov
Y1  - 1984/01/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1984.4277938
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1984.4277938
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 64
EP  - 73
VL  - 9
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A special case of self-fulfilling prophecy (SFP), the Pygmalion effect is the enhanced performance of subordinates of whom supervisors expect more. Pygmalion research in military and training situations is reviewed. Presented is a model of SFP at work involving supervisory expectancy, leadership, subordinate self-expectancy, motivation, and performance. Issues for future research and application are discussed, including how to raise expectations, which subordinates are influenced most, positive and negative Pygmalion, and ethical concerns.
AB  - A special case of self-fulfilling prophecy (SFP), the Pygmalion effect is the enhanced performance of subordinates of whom supervisors expect more. Pygmalion research in military and training situations is reviewed. Presented is a model of SFP at work involving supervisory expectancy, leadership, subordinate self-expectancy, motivation, and performance. Issues for future research and application are discussed, including how to raise expectations, which subordinates are influenced most, positive and negative Pygmalion, and ethical concerns.
SN  - 0363-7425
