T1  - The Development and Enforcement of Group Norms
AU  - Feldman, Daniel C.
Y1  - 1984/01/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1984.4277934
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1984.4277934
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 47
EP  - 53
VL  - 9
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This paper examines why group norms are enforced and how group norms develop. It is argued here that groups are likely to bring under normative control only those behaviors that ensure group survival, increase the predictability of group members' behavior, avoid embarrassing interpersonal situations, or give expression to the group's central values. Group norms develop through explicit statements by supervisors or co-workers, critical events in the group's history, primacy, or carry-over behaviors from past situations.
AB  - This paper examines why group norms are enforced and how group norms develop. It is argued here that groups are likely to bring under normative control only those behaviors that ensure group survival, increase the predictability of group members' behavior, avoid embarrassing interpersonal situations, or give expression to the group's central values. Group norms develop through explicit statements by supervisors or co-workers, critical events in the group's history, primacy, or carry-over behaviors from past situations.
